2.1 Smooth Manifolds and Lie Groups

Definition 2.1 (Smooth manifold).
A smooth manifold \mathcal{M} of dimension n is a Hausdorff, second‑countable topological space equipped with a smooth atlas of charts \{(U_\alpha,\varphi_\alpha)\} such that each \varphi_\alpha:U_\alpha\to\mathbb{R}^n is a homeomorphism and the transition maps \varphi_\beta\circ\varphi_\alpha^{-1} are C^\infty on their domains.

Definition 2.2 (Tangent space, vector field).
For a point p\in\mathcal{M}, the tangent space T_p\mathcal{M} is the vector space of derivations of smooth functions at p. A vector field X on \mathcal{M} is a smooth section of the tangent bundle T\mathcal{M}. The set of all vector fields is denoted \mathfrak{X}(\mathcal{M}).

Definition 2.3 (Lie bracket).
For X,Y\in\mathfrak{X}(\mathcal{M}), the Lie bracket [X,Y] is the unique vector field satisfying

[X,Y]f = X(Yf) - Y(Xf) \qquad \forall f\in C^\infty(\mathcal{M}).
\]  

The Lie bracket is bilinear, skew‑symmetric, and satisfies the Jacobi identity.

Definition 2.4 (Flow and exponential map).
The flow of a vector field X is a smooth map \Phi_X:\mathbb{R}\times\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{M} such that \Phi_X(0,p)=p and \frac{d}{dt}\Phi_X(t,p)=X(\Phi_X(t,p)). The exponential map \exp(tX)(p) := \Phi_X(t,p) defines the one‑parameter group generated by X.

Definition 2.5 (Lie group).
A Lie group G is a smooth manifold that is also a group such that multiplication and inversion are smooth maps. Its Lie algebra \mathfrak{g} is the tangent space at the identity T_eG equipped with the bracket induced by the Lie bracket of left‑invariant vector fields.

Theorem 2.6 (Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff formula).
Let \mathfrak{g} be a Lie algebra. For sufficiently small A,B\in\mathfrak{g} (in a Banach space sense),

\exp(A)\exp(B) = \exp\!\left( A + B + \frac12[A,B] + \frac1{12}[A,[A,B]] - \frac1{12}[B,[A,B]] + \cdots \right),
\]  

where the series converges absolutely.
Reference: Hall (2015), Theorem 3.41.

---

2.2 Riemannian Geometry

Definition 2.7 (Riemannian metric).
A Riemannian metric g on \mathcal{M} is a smooth assignment of an inner product g_p:T_p\mathcal{M}\times T_p\mathcal{M}\to\mathbb{R} for each p\in\mathcal{M}.

Definition 2.8 (Levi‑Civita connection).
The unique torsion‑free connection \nabla on \mathcal{M} that satisfies \nabla g=0 is the Levi‑Civita connection. In local coordinates, its Christoffel symbols are given by

\Gamma^k_{ij} = \frac12 g^{kl}\bigl(\partial_i g_{jl} + \partial_j g_{il} - \partial_l g_{ij}\bigr).

Definition 2.9 (Riemann curvature tensor).
For vector fields X,Y,Z,

R(X,Y)Z = \nabla_X\nabla_Y Z - \nabla_Y\nabla_X Z - \nabla_{[X,Y]}Z.
\]  

In local coordinates, R_{ijk}^l is defined by R(\partial_i,\partial_j)\partial_k = R_{ijk}^l \partial_l. The scalar curvature is

R = g^{ij} R_{ij}, \quad \text{where } R_{ij}=R_{ikj}^k.

---

2.3 Stochastic Processes and Martingales

Let (\Omega,\mathcal{F},\{\mathcal{F}_t\}_{t\ge0},\mathbb{P}) be a filtered probability space satisfying the usual conditions (right‑continuity and completeness). All processes are assumed adapted.

Definition 2.10 (Super‑martingale).
A real‑valued adapted process \{S_t\}_{t\ge0} is a super‑martingale if \mathbb{E}[|S_t|]<\infty for all t and for all 0\le s\le t,

\mathbb{E}[S_t\mid\mathcal{F}_s] \le S_s \quad \text{a.s.}
\]  

If equality holds, it is a martingale.

Theorem 2.11 (Doob’s maximal inequality).
Let \{S_t\} be a non‑negative super‑martingale. Then for any \lambda>0 and any bounded stopping time \tau,

\mathbb{P}\!\left( \sup_{0\le t\le\tau} S_t \ge \lambda \right) \le \frac{\mathbb{E}[S_0]}{\lambda}.

Theorem 2.12 (Optional stopping theorem).
If \tau is a bounded stopping time and \{S_t\} is a martingale (or super‑martingale with suitable integrability), then \mathbb{E}[S_\tau] = \mathbb{E}[S_0] (resp. \mathbb{E}[S_\tau]\le\mathbb{E}[S_0] for super‑martingale).

Theorem 2.13 (Snell envelope).
Given an adapted process \{U_t\} that is bounded below, the smallest super‑martingale dominating U_t is given by the Snell envelope

V_t = \operatorname{ess\,sup}_{\tau\ge t} \mathbb{E}[U_\tau\mid\mathcal{F}_t],
\]  

where the supremum is taken over all stopping times \tau\ge t. The stopping time \tau^* = \inf\{t\ge0 : V_t = U_t\} is optimal for the problem of maximizing \mathbb{E}[U_\tau] over stopping times.
Reference: Peskir & Shiryaev (2006), Chapter 2.

---

2.4 Viability Theory

Definition 2.14 (Viability kernel).
Consider a control system \dot x = f(x,u) with u\in U(x). For a closed set K\subset\mathcal{M}, the viability kernel \operatorname{Viab}(K) is the set of initial states from which there exists a control u(\cdot) such that the solution stays in K for all t\ge0.
Reference: Aubin (2009), Chapter 3.

---

2.5 Persistent Homology

Definition 2.15 (Filtration).
A filtration of a simplicial complex X is an increasing family \{X_r\}_{r\in\mathbb{R}} of subcomplexes. The persistence module \{H_p(X_r)\} tracks how homology classes appear and disappear.

Definition 2.16 (Barcode).
A persistence barcode is a multiset of intervals [b,d) representing the birth and death times of homology classes.
Reference: Edelsbrunner & Harer (2010), Chapter VII.

---

2.6 Category Theory

Definition 2.17 (Monoidal category).
A strict monoidal category \mathcal{C} consists of a category, a bifunctor \otimes:\mathcal{C}\times\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{C} that is associative, and a unit object I such that I\otimes X = X = X\otimes I.
Reference: Lawvere & Schanuel (2009), Part III.

