Chapter 3: A Concrete Physical Model: 1‑D Relativistic Deceleration

To ground the abstract framework, we introduce a minimal but physically meaningful model that exhibits non‑commutativity between a deceleration action and an observation action.

---

3.1 System State

Consider a spacecraft moving in one dimension with velocity v\in(-c,c). The mission state is

\Psi = (v,\;\theta,\;\mathcal{E}),
\]  

where:

· v is velocity (positive toward target),
· \theta is the uncertainty (standard deviation) in the estimated position of the target star,
· \mathcal{E} is the remaining fuel energy (or total delta‑v budget).

The target star is assumed to be at rest relative to the solar system, with known rest‑frame frequency f_0.

---

3.2 Operators

Deceleration operator D:
Apply a thrust impulse that changes velocity by -\Delta v (with \Delta v>0), consuming fuel \Delta v (in energy units).

D(v,\theta,\mathcal{E}) = (v-\Delta v,\;\theta,\;\mathcal{E}-\Delta v),
\]  

where we assume the fuel constraint \mathcal{E}-\Delta v\ge0 holds.

Observation operator O:
Perform a measurement of the star’s frequency to infer relative velocity. The measurement precision depends on the current velocity due to the relativistic Doppler shift. The observed frequency is

f_{\text{obs}} = f_0\sqrt{\frac{1-\beta}{1+\beta}},\quad \beta = v/c.
\]  

We model the velocity uncertainty after measurement as

\sigma_{\text{post}} = \frac{\sigma_{\text{pre}} \cdot \sigma_{\text{sensor}}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{\text{pre}}^2 + \sigma_{\text{sensor}}^2}},
\]  

where \sigma_{\text{sensor}} is the sensor’s intrinsic uncertainty, which worsens at high velocities because of the Doppler broadening. We take

\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v) = \frac{\sigma_0}{\sqrt{1-\beta^2}},
\]  

with \sigma_0 the rest‑frame uncertainty. Since the position uncertainty \theta is related to the velocity uncertainty by a constant factor (the time elapsed), we absorb that factor into the definition and treat \theta directly as the standard deviation of the position estimate. Thus the observation updates \theta as

O(v,\theta,\mathcal{E}) = \left(v,\; \theta\cdot\frac{\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)}{\sqrt{\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)^2}},\; \mathcal{E}\right).
\]  

The fuel \mathcal{E} is unchanged.

---

3.3 Explicit Commutator Magnitude

We compute the commutator [D,O]_\Psi = D(O(\Psi)) - O(D(\Psi)). Only the \theta component changes.

\begin{aligned}
\theta_{DO} &= \theta \cdot \frac{\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v-\Delta v)}{\sqrt{\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v-\Delta v)^2}}, \\
\theta_{OD} &= \theta \cdot \frac{\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)}{\sqrt{\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)^2}}.
\end{aligned}
\]  

Hence

[D,O]_\Psi = \theta\left( \frac{\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v-\Delta v)}{\sqrt{\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v-\Delta v)^2}} - \frac{\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)}{\sqrt{\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)^2}} \right).

Proposition 3.1 (First‑order expansion).
For small \Delta v,

[D,O]_\Psi = -\theta \frac{\theta^2 \sigma_{\text{sensor}}'(v)}{(\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)^2)^{3/2}} \Delta v + O(\Delta v^2),
\]  

where \sigma_{\text{sensor}}'(v) = \frac{\sigma_0 \beta}{c (1-\beta^2)^{3/2}}. Explicitly,

[D,O]_\Psi = -\frac{\theta^3 \sigma_0 \beta}{c (1-\beta^2)^{3/2} \bigl(\theta^2 + \sigma_0^2/(1-\beta^2)\bigr)^{3/2}} \Delta v + O(\Delta v^2).

Proof. The derivative of the function h(v)=\frac{\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)}{\sqrt{\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)^2}} is

h'(v) = \frac{\theta^2 \sigma_{\text{sensor}}'(v)}{(\theta^2+\sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v)^2)^{3/2}}.
\]  

Then h(v-\Delta v) = h(v) - h'(v)\Delta v + O(\Delta v^2). The result follows by substituting the expression for \sigma_{\text{sensor}}'(v). ∎

The commutator becomes significant when \beta is close to 1 (relativistic regime) and when the initial uncertainty \theta is comparable to \sigma_{\text{sensor}}(v). This explicit form confirms that non‑commutativity is a physical consequence of special relativity.

---

3.4 Physical Interpretation and Implications

The commutator [D,O]_\Psi quantifies the difference in final uncertainty depending on whether we decelerate first or observe first. If we observe first at high velocity, the sensor’s large uncertainty yields little improvement; decelerating first reduces velocity, improving the subsequent observation, leading to a smaller final uncertainty. Thus the order matters: observation before deceleration is suboptimal when the goal is to reduce uncertainty.

This model serves as a testbed for the non‑commutative control framework. In later chapters we will incorporate the fuel constraint and design control policies that account for the ordering penalty.

