Chapter 5: Optimal Refusal as a Stopping Time

In this chapter we formalize the notion of refusal—the deliberate choice to cease acting—as an optimal strategy for preserving safety when all admissible actions either increase expected risk or would leave the safe set. We work in a discrete‑time stochastic setting and prove that refusal is an optimal stopping time that maximizes the expected time until exit from a safe region.

---

5.1 Setup and Definitions

Let (\Omega,\mathcal{F},\{\mathcal{F}_t\}_{t=0}^\infty,\mathbb{P}) be a filtered probability space with discrete time t=0,1,2,\dots. The state process X_t takes values in a smooth manifold \mathcal{M} and is adapted to \mathcal{F}_t. At each time, we choose an operator O_t from a set \mathcal{A} of admissible operators. The operators are measurable maps O:\mathcal{M}\to\mathcal{M}.

Safe set. Let K\subset\mathcal{M} be a closed set representing the safe region. We assume K has non‑empty interior and a smooth boundary \partial K. A mission is safe if X_t\in K for all t.

Safety metric. Let s:\mathcal{M}\to[0,\infty) be a continuous function satisfying:

· s(x)>0 for all x\in K,
· s(x)=0 for all x\notin K (or at least on the complement of K),
· s is L_s-Lipschitz with respect to a Riemannian metric on \mathcal{M},
· For convenience, we assume s(x)\ge\operatorname{dist}(x,\partial K) for all x\in K (this can always be arranged by scaling).

Define the safety process S_t = s(X_t). The process S_t is non‑negative and adapted.

Super‑martingale condition. We say that a policy (sequence of operators) is safe if it satisfies the super‑martingale condition:

\mathbb{E}[S_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{F}_t] \le S_t \quad \text{a.s. for all } t.

This condition means that the expected safety does not increase; it can only stay the same or decrease. It is a natural mathematical expression of the idea that safety can only be preserved or lost, never gained without active intervention.

---

5.2 The Refusal Stopping Time

We now define the refusal stopping time as the first time when every available operator would violate the super‑martingale condition or would immediately exit the safe set.

Definition 5.1 (Refusal stopping time).
Let \tau be defined by

\tau = \inf\left\{ t\ge 0 \;:\; \forall O\in\mathcal{A},\; \mathbb{E}[S_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{F}_t] > S_t \ \text{or}\ O(X_t)\notin K \right\}.

If the set is empty, we set \tau=\infty.

At time \tau, no admissible action can keep the system in the safe region while preserving the super‑martingale property. Hence the only safe choice is to refuse to act.

Definition 5.2 (Refusal operator).
The refusal operator \varnothing is defined by \varnothing(X_t) = X_t. That is, it leaves the state unchanged. After time \tau, we apply \varnothing for all subsequent times: X_{t+1} = X_t for t\ge\tau.

---

5.3 Optimality Theorem

Theorem 5.3 (Optimal refusal).
Assume that under any admissible policy, the safety process S_t is a non‑negative super‑martingale. Then the policy that stops at \tau (i.e., applies \varnothing for all t\ge\tau) maximizes the expected time until exit from K among all policies that keep S_t a super‑martingale. Moreover,

\mathbb{P}\bigl( \exists t\ge0 : X_t\notin K \bigr) \le \frac{\mathbb{E}[S_0]}{\min_{x\in\partial K} s(x)}.

Proof. The proof proceeds in several steps.

Step 1: \tau is a stopping time.

We need to show that for each t, the event \{\tau \le t\} is \mathcal{F}_t-measurable. The condition “\mathbb{E}[S_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{F}_t] > S_t” is \mathcal{F}_t-measurable because the conditional expectation is a measurable function of the \mathcal{F}_t-measurable random variables; the inequality defines a measurable set. The condition “O(X_t)\notin K” is \mathcal{F}_t-measurable because X_t is \mathcal{F}_t-measurable and O is measurable. Thus \{\tau = t\} is \mathcal{F}_t-measurable, and \tau is a stopping time.

Step 2: Under the refusal policy, S_{t\wedge\tau} is a super‑martingale.

For t < \tau, by definition there exists an operator that preserves the super‑martingale property; we assume the policy chooses such an operator. At t=\tau, we switch to \varnothing, and for t>\tau, S_t = S_\tau. Hence for all t\ge\tau, \mathbb{E}[S_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{F}_t] = S_t (a martingale). Therefore the stopped process S_{t\wedge\tau} is a super‑martingale.

Step 3: Optimality via the Snell envelope.

Consider the optimal stopping problem

V_0 = \sup_{\sigma} \mathbb{E}[S_\sigma],

where \sigma ranges over all stopping times such that the policy respects the super‑martingale condition. By the Snell envelope theory (Theorem 2.13), the value V_t is the smallest super‑martingale dominating S_t, and the optimal stopping time is \tau^* = \inf\{t\ge0 : V_t = S_t\}. We claim that \tau defined above coincides with \tau^*. Indeed, for any t<\tau^*, there exists some operator that keeps V_t above S_t; this operator also keeps S_t a super‑martingale because V_t dominates S_t. Conversely, at t=\tau^*, all operators would cause V_{t+1}<V_t or would leave K, which is exactly the condition defining \tau. Hence \tau = \tau^*. Consequently, the refusal policy achieves the supremum \mathbb{E}[S_\tau]. Since S_t>0 inside K and zero outside, maximizing \mathbb{E}[S_\tau] is equivalent to maximizing the expected time until exit (or, more precisely, minimizing the probability of early exit). Therefore the refusal policy is optimal.

Step 4: Probability bound.

Let \epsilon = \min_{x\in\partial K} s(x). By the Lipschitz property and the assumption s(x)\ge\operatorname{dist}(x,\partial K), we have s(x)\ge\epsilon for all x\in K (the minimum on the boundary is attained because K is closed). Consider the stopped super‑martingale S_{t\wedge\tau}. Since it is non‑negative, we can apply Doob’s maximal inequality (Theorem 2.11) to obtain for any \lambda>0,

\mathbb{P}\!\left( \sup_{0\le t\le T} S_{t\wedge\tau} \ge \lambda \right) \le \frac{\mathbb{E}[S_0]}{\lambda},

for any fixed horizon T. Let T\to\infty; the inequality holds for the supremum over all t. Now note that the event \{ \exists t : X_t\notin K \} implies that before exiting, the process must cross the boundary, and at the first exit time we have S_t \le \epsilon (since s is continuous and zero outside). In fact, if the process ever leaves K, then \sup_t S_t \ge \epsilon (because it must pass through \epsilon on the boundary). Therefore

\mathbb{P}(\exists t: X_t\notin K) \le \mathbb{P}\!\left( \sup_t S_{t\wedge\tau} \ge \epsilon \right) \le \frac{\mathbb{E}[S_0]}{\epsilon}.

This completes the proof. ∎

---

5.4 Discussion

The theorem shows that refusing to act when no safe action exists is not merely a fallback but the optimal strategy. The bound on the probability of exit is explicit and depends only on the initial safety level and the minimal safety on the boundary. This is a strong safety guarantee.

In practice, the condition that all operators either increase expected risk or leave the safe set may be difficult to verify online. However, one can compute a safe set K and a safety metric s such that the super‑martingale condition holds by construction. For example, one can use barrier functions or control Lyapunov functions. The refusal strategy then acts as a “last resort” that guarantees the probability bound.

The next chapters will use this result to derive quantitative safety guarantees in the presence of non‑commutativity.

