Appendix B: Martingale Convergence and Optimal Stopping Proofs

This appendix provides the rigorous details for the martingale arguments used in Chapter 5.

B.1 Doob’s Convergence Theorem for Super‑Martingales

Theorem B.1 (Doob’s Convergence Theorem).
Let \{S_t\}_{t=0}^\infty be a non‑negative super‑martingale. Then S_\infty := \lim_{t\to\infty} S_t exists almost surely and \mathbb{E}[S_\infty] \le \mathbb{E}[S_0].

Proof. For a super‑martingale, the number of upcrossings of an interval [a,b] with 0<a<b is almost surely finite. Taking a countable dense set of intervals yields convergence. The inequality follows from Fatou’s lemma. See e.g., Karatzas & Shreve (1998), Theorem 1.3.15. ∎

B.2 Optimal Stopping and the Snell Envelope

Definition B.2 (Snell envelope).
Let \{U_t\} be an adapted process bounded below. The Snell envelope is

V_t = \operatorname{ess\,sup}_{\tau\ge t} \mathbb{E}[U_\tau\mid\mathcal{F}_t],

where the supremum is over all stopping times \tau\ge t. The process V_t is the smallest super‑martingale dominating U_t.

Theorem B.3 (Optimal stopping).
The stopping time \tau^* = \inf\{t\ge0 : V_t = U_t\} is optimal for the problem \sup_{\tau} \mathbb{E}[U_\tau], provided U_t is right‑continuous and the family \{U_\tau\} is uniformly integrable.

Proof. See Peskir & Shiryaev (2006), Chapter 2. ∎

B.3 Proof of Theorem 5.3 (Optimal Refusal)

We restate the theorem and provide a complete proof using the Snell envelope.

Theorem (Optimal refusal).
Under the assumptions of Chapter 5, the refusal stopping time \tau defined by

\tau = \inf\{t\ge0: \forall O\in\mathcal{A},\ \mathbb{E}[S_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{F}_t] > S_t \text{ or } O(X_t)\notin K\}

is optimal for maximizing \mathbb{E}[\tau] among policies that keep S_t a super‑martingale. Moreover,

\mathbb{P}(\exists t: X_t\notin K) \le \frac{\mathbb{E}[S_0]}{\min_{x\in\partial K}s(x)}.

Proof.

1. Stopping time property. The event \{\tau = t\} depends only on X_0,\dots,X_t and the conditional expectations, which are \mathcal{F}_t-measurable. Hence \tau is a stopping time.
2. Super‑martingale under refusal. For t<\tau, by definition there exists an operator that satisfies \mathbb{E}[S_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{F}_t] \le S_t and O(X_t)\in K. Assume the policy chooses such an operator. For t\ge\tau, we set X_{t+1}=X_t, so S_{t+1}=S_t. Hence \mathbb{E}[S_{t+1}\mid\mathcal{F}_t] = S_t. Thus the stopped process S_{t\wedge\tau} is a super‑martingale.
3. Relation to Snell envelope. Define U_t = S_t and let V_t be its Snell envelope. By construction, V_t is the largest super‑martingale that is less than or equal to S_t? Actually the Snell envelope is the smallest super‑martingale dominating U_t. We are interested in maximizing \mathbb{E}[S_\sigma]; the optimal stopping time is the first time V_t = S_t. We claim that \tau coincides with this time. Indeed, for any t<\tau, there exists an operator that preserves the super‑martingale property, which implies that V_t > S_t (otherwise stopping would be optimal). At t=\tau, no such operator exists, so V_t = S_t. Therefore \tau is the optimal stopping time.
4. Probability bound. Since S_t is a non‑negative super‑martingale, Doob’s maximal inequality gives for any \lambda>0:
   \mathbb{P}\bigl(\sup_{t\ge0} S_t \ge \lambda\bigr) \le \frac{\mathbb{E}[S_0]}{\lambda}.
   Choose \lambda = \min_{x\in\partial K} s(x). Because s(x)\ge \operatorname{dist}(x,\partial K) and s(x)=0 outside K, the event \{X_t\notin K\} implies that at the first exit time, S_t \ge \lambda (the state must cross the boundary). Hence
   \mathbb{P}(\exists t: X_t\notin K) \le \mathbb{P}(\sup_t S_t \ge \lambda) \le \frac{\mathbb{E}[S_0]}{\lambda}.
   ∎

