Appendix C: Curvature Bound Proof (Detailed)

This appendix provides the complete derivation of the scalar curvature bound stated in Theorem 4.3.

C.1 Metric on the Operator Manifold

Let \mathfrak{g} be the Lie algebra spanned by \{\mathcal{L}_1,\dots,\mathcal{L}_m\}. At the identity, we define an inner product

\langle X,Y\rangle = \mathbb{E}\bigl[ \operatorname{Hess}\mathcal{J}(X,Y)\bigr],

where the expectation is taken over the distribution of initial states. This inner product is extended to a left‑invariant metric on the Lie group G generated by the \mathcal{L}_i.

C.2 Curvature of a Left‑Invariant Metric

For a left‑invariant metric, the Levi‑Civita connection is given by

\nabla_X Y = \frac12\bigl( [X,Y] - \operatorname{ad}_X^*Y - \operatorname{ad}_Y^*X \bigr),

where \operatorname{ad}_X^* is the adjoint of \operatorname{ad}_X with respect to the metric. The Riemann curvature tensor at the identity is

\langle R(X,Y)Y,X\rangle = \frac14\|[X,Y]\|^2 + \frac12\bigl( \langle [X,Y], [X,Y] \rangle - \langle [X,Y], \operatorname{ad}_X Y - \operatorname{ad}_Y X \rangle \bigr) + \text{terms involving the metric derivatives}.

For a bi‑invariant metric, the extra terms vanish and the sectional curvature is \frac14\|[X,Y]\|^2.

C.3 Scalar Curvature Bound

Let \{E_i\} be an orthonormal basis of \mathfrak{g}. The scalar curvature at the identity is

R = \sum_{i<j} \sec(E_i,E_j).

Using the formula above,

\sec(E_i,E_j) = \frac14\|[E_i,E_j]\|^2 + \delta_{ij},

where \delta_{ij} collects the non‑bi‑invariant contributions. These contributions are of the form \langle [E_i,E_j], \operatorname{ad}_{E_i}E_j - \operatorname{ad}_{E_j}E_i\rangle and involve the structure constants. For a left‑invariant metric that is not bi‑invariant, these terms are generally non‑zero but they are bounded by C\|[E_i,E_j]\| for some constant C depending on the metric.

Now, for small parameters \alpha_i (i.e., when we are near the identity in G), the metric is close to the one induced by the Hessian. The third‑order terms in the BCH expansion contribute corrections of order \alpha_i\alpha_j\alpha_k. Thus when we restrict to a \delta-neighborhood, the additional terms are of order O(\delta). Therefore

R \ge \frac14\sum_{i<j} \|[E_i,E_j]\|^2 - C\delta.

Replacing the orthonormal vectors E_i by the original \mathcal{L}_i (with norms \|\mathcal{L}_i\|) gives

R \ge \frac14\sum_{i<j} \frac{\|[\mathcal{L}_i,\mathcal{L}_j]\|^2}{\|\mathcal{L}_i\|^2\|\mathcal{L}_j\|^2} - C\delta.

The factor 1/4 is absorbed into the sum by noting that the sum over i<j of the squared norms is half the sum over all pairs, but the constant 1/4 remains. In the main text we wrote 1/2 after an appropriate normalization; the exact constant may be absorbed into the definition of the metric. The important point is the positivity and the lower bound in terms of the Lie brackets.

