Appendix D: Persistent Homology for Safety

This appendix gives the topological background for the homological safety invariant introduced in Chapter 7.

D.1 Simplicial Complexes and Filtrations

A simplicial complex X is a collection of simplices (points, edges, triangles, etc.) such that faces of simplices are in X. A filtration is a nested family

X_0 \subset X_1 \subset \dots \subset X_n = X.

In our context, we consider the reachable set R(\varepsilon) as \varepsilon varies (e.g., the set of states reachable with operator magnitudes bounded by \varepsilon). The filtration can be built by discretizing the state space and constructing a Čech or Vietoris–Rips complex.

D.2 Persistence Modules and Barcodes

For each p, the homology groups H_p(X_r) form a persistence module. The persistence barcode records the intervals [b,d) during which a homology class appears. For a fixed filtration, the barcode can be computed algorithmically.

D.3 Homological Refusal Invariant

Theorem D.1 (Homological refusal invariant).
Let \gamma be a sequence of operators whose induced path in the safe set K is not null‑homotopic (i.e., [\gamma]\neq0 in H_1(K;\mathbb{Z})). Then any continuous realization of \gamma must at some time leave K. Hence, to guarantee safety, the refusal operator must be invoked before executing \gamma.

Proof. Suppose the path lies entirely in K. Then it is a continuous map from the interval [0,1] into K. If it were possible to stay in K, the path would be a representative of its homology class in H_1(K). The condition [\gamma]\neq0 means the path is not homologous to zero, i.e., it cannot be contracted to a point within K. This is a contradiction. Therefore the path cannot remain in K. ∎

In practice, we compute the persistence barcode of the reachable set R(\varepsilon) for a range of \varepsilon. If a homology class persists for all \varepsilon up to the maximum allowed magnitude, then any path that would realize that homology class is topologically forced to exit K for sufficiently small perturbations, making it unsafe.

