Appendix E: Technical Lemmas and Inequalities

E.1 Grönwall’s Lemma

Lemma E.1 (Grönwall).
Let u(t) be a non‑negative continuous function satisfying

u(t) \le a + b\int_0^t u(s)\,ds \quad \text{for } t\ge0,

with a,b\ge0. Then u(t) \le a e^{bt}.

Proof. Standard; see Hale (2009). ∎

E.2 Lipschitz Estimates for Flows

Lemma E.2 (Flow difference).
Let X and Y be vector fields on \mathcal{M} with Lipschitz constant L. Then for the flows \Phi_X^t and \Phi_Y^t,

\operatorname{dist}\bigl(\Phi_X^t(p),\Phi_Y^t(p)\bigr) \le \frac{e^{Lt}-1}{L} \sup_{s\in[0,t]} \|X(\Phi_X^s(p))-Y(\Phi_X^s(p))\|.

Proof. Differentiate the distance and apply Grönwall. ∎

E.3 Baker–Campbell–Hausdorff Remainder Bounds

Lemma E.3 (BCH remainder).
For A,B in a Banach Lie algebra, if \|A\|,\|B\|\le r, then

\bigl\| \log(\exp(A)\exp(B)) - (A+B+\tfrac12[A,B]) \bigr\| \le C r^3,

where C depends only on the Lie algebra structure constants.

Proof. See Hall (2015), Theorem 3.41 and subsequent estimates. ∎

